  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some common myths that are not true?",
  "response": "There are numerous myths and misconceptions that persist despite evidence to the contrary. Here are some common ones:\n\n---\n\n### **Health and Body Myths**\n1. **Myth:** We only use 10% of our brain.  \n   **Truth:** Brain imaging shows that nearly all parts of the brain are active at some point during the day.\n\n2. **Myth:** Cracking your knuckles causes arthritis.  \n   **Truth:** No scientific evidence links knuckle cracking to arthritis. It\u2019s just gas bubbles popping in the joints.\n\n3. **Myth:** You need to drink 8 glasses of water a day.  \n   **Truth:** Hydration needs vary by person, activity level, and climate. Many people get enough water from food and beverages.\n\n4. **Myth:** Sugar makes kids hyperactive.  \n   **Truth:** Studies show no direct link between sugar and hyperactivity. The perceived effect is often due to excitement or context (e.g., parties).\n\n---\n\n### **Nature and Science Myths**\n5. **Myth:** Lightning never strikes the same place twice.  \n   **Truth:** Lightning often strikes the same place repeatedly, especially tall structures like the Empire State Building.\n\n6. **Myth:** Goldfish have a 3-second memory.  \n   **Truth:** Goldfish can remember things for months and even be trained to perform tasks.\n\n7. **Myth:** Bats are blind.  \n   **Truth:** Most bats can see, and many use echolocation to navigate in the dark.\n\n---\n\n### **Food and Nutrition Myths**\n8. **Myth:** Carrots improve your eyesight.  \n   **Truth:** While carrots are rich in vitamin A, which is essential for eye health, they don\u2019t improve vision beyond normal levels.\n\n9. **Myth:** Eating late at night causes weight gain.  \n   **Truth:** Weight gain is caused by consuming more calories than you burn, regardless of when you eat.\n\n10. **Myth:** MSG (monosodium glutamate) is harmful.  \n    **Truth:** MSG is safe for most people and is naturally present in many foods like tomatoes and cheese.\n\n---\n\n### **Historical and Cultural Myths**\n11. **Myth:** Vikings wore horned helmets.  \n    **Truth:** There\u2019s no evidence Vikings wore horned helmets. This idea was popularized by 19th-century art and opera.\n\n12. **Myth:** Napoleon was unusually short.  \n    **Truth:** Napoleon was about 5\u20196\u201d (168 cm), average height for his time. The misconception likely stems from British propaganda.\n\n13. **Myth:** The Great Wall of China is visible from space.  \n    **Truth:** The Great Wall is not visible to the naked eye from space. It\u2019s too narrow and blends into its surroundings.\n\n---\n\n### **Technology and Everyday Myths**\n14. **Myth:** Dropping a penny from a skyscraper can kill someone.  \n    **Truth:** A penny\u2019s terminal velocity is too low to cause serious harm.\n\n15. **Myth:** Cell phones cause cancer.  \n    **Truth:** Extensive research has found no conclusive link between cell phone use and cancer.\n\n16. **Myth:** You should let your phone battery die completely before recharging.  \n    **Truth:** Modern lithium-ion batteries perform best when kept between 20% and 80% charge.\n\n---\n\n### **Animal Myths**\n17. **Myth:** Ostriches bury their heads in the sand.  \n    **Truth:** Ostriches don\u2019t bury their heads; they sometimes lower them to eat or turn their eggs.\n\n18. **Myth:** Handling a baby bird will make its mother abandon it.  \n    **Truth:** Birds have a poor sense of smell and won\u2019t abandon their chicks due to human scent.\n\n---\n\n### **Psychological Myths**\n19. **Myth:** Opposites attract in relationships.  \n    **Truth:** Research shows people are more likely to form long-term relationships with those who share similar values and interests.\n\n20. **Myth:** People with mental illness are more violent.  \n    **Truth:** Most people with mental illness are not violent, and they are more likely to be victims of violence than perpetrators.\n\n---\n\nThese myths persist due to cultural storytelling, misinformation, or simple misunderstandings, but they can often be debunked with critical thinking and scientific evidence!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
